[src:laplace-transform/inverse-laplace-transform] It can be proven that, if a function F has the inverse Laplace transform ŌüĀ f ŌüĀ, then f is uniquely determined (considering functions that differ from each other only on a point set having Lebesgue measure zero as the same).
[src:laplace-transform/inverse-laplace-transform] This result was first proven by Mathias Lerch in 1903 and is known as Lerch's theorem.
[src:laplace-transform/inverse-laplace-transform] The Laplace transform and the inverse Laplace transform together have a number of properties that make them useful for analysing linear dynamical systems.
[src:laplace-transform/inverse-laplace-transform] There is an integral formula for the inverse Laplace transform, called the *Mellin's inversion formula*.
