[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The functions are often denoted using a lowercase symbol for the time-domain function and the corresponding uppercase symbol for the frequency-domain function, e.g. $x(t)$ and ŌüĀ $X(s)$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The transform is useful for converting differentiation and integration in the time domain into the algebraic operations multiplication and division in the Laplace domain (analogous to how logarithms are useful for simplifying multiplication and division into addition and subtraction).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Once solved, the inverse Laplace transform can be used to transform it to the original domain.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This is often aided by referencing tables such as that given below.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is defined (for suitable functions ŌüĀ f ŌüĀ) by the integral ${\mathcal {L}}\{f\}(s)=\int _{0}^{\infty }f(t)e^{-st}\,dt,$ where ŌüĀ s ŌüĀ is a complex number.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is related to many other transforms.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] It is essentially the same as the Mellin transform and is closely related to the Fourier transform.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Unlike for the Fourier transform, the Laplace transform of a function is often an analytic function, meaning that it can be expressed as a power series that converges locally, the coefficients of which represent the moments of the original function.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Moreover, the techniques of complex analysis, especially contour integrals, can be used for simplifying calculations.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is named after mathematician and astronomer Pierre-Simon, Marquis de Laplace, who used a similar transform in his work on probability theory.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Laplace wrote extensively about the use of generating functions (1814), and the integral form of the Laplace transform evolved naturally as a result.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Laplace's use of generating functions was similar to what is now known as the z-transform, and he gave little attention to the continuous variable case which was discussed by Niels Henrik Abel.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] From 1744, Leonhard Euler investigated integrals of the form $z=\int X(x)e^{ax}\,dx\quad {\text{ and }}\quad z=\int X(x)x^{A}\,dx$ as solutions of differential equations, introducing in particular the gamma function.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Joseph-Louis Lagrange was an admirer of Euler and, in his work on integrating probability density functions, investigated expressions of the form $\int X(x)e^{-ax}a^{x}\,dx,$ which resembles a Laplace transform.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] These types of integrals seem first to have attracted Laplace's attention in 1782, where he was following in the spirit of Euler in using the integrals themselves as solutions of equations.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] However, in 1785, Laplace took the critical step forward when, rather than simply looking for a solution in the form of an integral, he started to apply the transforms in the sense that was later to become popular.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] He used an integral of the form $\int x^{s}\varphi (x)\,dx,$ akin to a Mellin transform, to transform the whole of a difference equation, in order to look for solutions of the transformed equation.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] He then went on to apply the Laplace transform in the same way and started to derive some of its properties, beginning to appreciate its potential power.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Laplace also recognised that Joseph Fourier's method of Fourier series for solving the diffusion equation could only apply to a limited region of space, because those solutions were periodic.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In 1809, Laplace applied his transform to find solutions that diffused indefinitely in space.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In 1821, Cauchy developed an operational calculus for the Laplace transform that could be used to study linear differential equations in much the same way the transform is now used in basic engineering.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This method was popularized, and perhaps rediscovered, by Oliver Heaviside around the turn of the century.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Bernhard Riemann used the Laplace transform in his 1859 paper *On the number of primes less than a given magnitude*, in which he also developed the inversion theorem.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Riemann used the Laplace transform to develop the functional equation of the Riemann zeta function, and his method is still used to relate the modular transformation law of the Jacobi theta function, which is readily proved via Poisson summation, to the functional equation.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Hjalmar Mellin was among the first to study the Laplace transform rigorously in the Karl Weierstrass school of analysis, and apply it to the study of differential equations and special functions, at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] At around the same time, Heaviside was busy with his operational calculus.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Thomas Joannes Stieltjes considered a generalization of the Laplace transform connected to his work on moments.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Other contributors in this time period included Mathias Lerch, Oliver Heaviside, and Thomas Bromwich.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In 1929, Vannevar Bush and Norbert Wiener published *Operational Circuit Analysis* as a text for engineering analysis of electrical circuits, applying both Fourier transforms and operational calculus, and in which they included one of the first predecessors of the modern table of Laplace transforms.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In 1934, Raymond Paley and Norbert Wiener published the important work *Fourier transforms in the complex domain*, about what is now called the Laplace transform (see below).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Also during the 30s, the Laplace transform was instrumental in Godfrey Harold Hardy and John Edensor Littlewood's study of tauberian theorems, and this application was later expounded on by Widder (1941), who developed other aspects of the theory such as a new method for inversion.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Edward Charles Titchmarsh wrote the influential *Introduction to the theory of the Fourier integral* (1937).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The current widespread use of the transform (mainly in engineering) came about during and soon after World War II, replacing the earlier Heaviside operational calculus.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The advantages of the Laplace transform had been emphasized by Gustav Doetsch.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] where s is a complex frequency-domain parameter ${\textstyle s=\sigma +i\omega }$ with real numbers Žā and Žē.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] An alternate notation for the Laplace transform is ${\mathcal {L}}\{f\}$ instead of *F*.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This is often written, especially in engineering settings, as ŌüĀ $F(s)={\mathcal {L}}\{f(t)\}$ ŌüĀ, with the understanding that the dummy variable t does not appear in the function ŌüĀ $F(s)$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The meaning of the integral depends on types of functions of interest.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] A necessary condition for existence of the integral is that f must be locally integrable on [0, Ōł×).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] For locally integrable functions that decay at infinity or are of exponential type (ŌüĀ $\vert f(t)\vert \leq Ae^{B\vert t\vert }$ ŌüĀ), the integral can be understood to be a (proper) Lebesgue integral.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] However, for many applications it is necessary to regard it as a conditionally convergent improper integral at Ōł×.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Still more generally, the integral can be understood in a weak sense, and this is dealt with below.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] An important special case is where ╬╝ is a probability measure, for example, the Dirac delta function.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In operational calculus, the Laplace transform of a measure is often treated as though the measure came from a probability density function f.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This limit emphasizes that any point mass located at 0 is entirely captured by the Laplace transform.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Although with the Lebesgue integral, it is not necessary to take such a limit, it does appear more naturally in connection with the LaplaceŌĆōStieltjes transform.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] When one says "the Laplace transform" without qualification, the unilateral or one-sided transform is usually intended.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform can be alternatively defined as the *bilateral Laplace transform*, or two-sided Laplace transform, by extending the limits of integration to be the entire real axis.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] If that is done, the common unilateral transform becomes a special case of the bilateral transform, where the definition of the function being transformed includes being multiplied by the Heaviside step function.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] An alternate notation for the bilateral Laplace transform is ŌüĀ ${\mathcal {B}}\{f\}$ ŌüĀ, instead of F.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Two integrable functions have the same Laplace transform only if they differ on a set of Lebesgue measure zero.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This means that, on the range of the transform, there is an inverse transform.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In fact, besides integrable functions, the Laplace transform is a one-to-one mapping from one function space into another in many other function spaces as well, although there is usually no easy characterization of the range.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Typical function spaces in which this is true include the spaces of bounded continuous functions, the space *L*Ōł×(0, Ōł×), or more generally tempered distributions on (0, Ōł×).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is also defined and injective for suitable spaces of tempered distributions.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In these cases, the image of the Laplace transform lives in a space of analytic functions in the region of convergence.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] where ╬│ is a real number so that the contour path of integration is in the region of convergence of *F*(*s*).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In most applications, the contour can be closed, allowing the use of the residue theorem.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] An alternative formula for the inverse Laplace transform is given by Post's inversion formula.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The limit here is interpreted in the weak-* topology.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In practice, it is typically more convenient to decompose a Laplace transform into known transforms of functions obtained from a table and construct the inverse by inspection.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In pure and applied probability, the Laplace transform is defined as an expected value.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] If X is a random variable with probability density function f, then the Laplace transform of f is given by the expectation ${\mathcal {L}}\{f\}(s)=\operatorname {E} \left[e^{-sX}\right],$ where $\operatorname {E} [r]$ is the expectation of random variable ŌüĀ r ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] By convention, this is referred to as the Laplace transform of the random variable X itself.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Here, replacing s by ŌłÆ*t* gives the moment generating function of X.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform has applications throughout probability theory, including first passage times of stochastic processes such as Markov chains, and renewal theory.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform can be alternatively defined in a purely algebraic manner by applying a field of fractions construction to the convolution ring of functions on the positive half-line.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The resulting space of abstract operators is exactly equivalent to Laplace space, but in this construction the forward and reverse transforms never need to be explicitly defined (avoiding the related difficulties with proving convergence).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] If *f* is a locally integrable function (or more generally a Borel measure locally of bounded variation), then the Laplace transform *F*(*s*) of *f* converges provided that the limit $\lim _{R\to \infty }\int _{0}^{R}f(t)e^{-st}\,dt$ exists.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform converges absolutely if the integral $\int _{0}^{\infty }\left|f(t)e^{-st}\right|\,dt$ exists as a proper Lebesgue integral.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is usually understood as conditionally convergent, meaning that it converges in the former but not in the latter sense.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The set of values for which *F*(*s*) converges absolutely is either of the form Re(*s*) > *a* or Re(*s*) Ōēź *a*, where *a* is an extended real constant with ŌłÆŌł× Ōēż *a* Ōēż Ōł× (a consequence of the dominated convergence theorem).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The constant *a* is known as the abscissa of absolute convergence, and depends on the growth behavior of *f*(*t*).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Analogously, the two-sided transform converges absolutely in a strip of the form *a* < Re(*s*) < *b*, and possibly including the lines Re(*s*) = *a* or Re(*s*) = *b*.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The subset of values of *s* for which the Laplace transform converges absolutely is called the region of absolute convergence, or the domain of absolute convergence.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In the two-sided case, it is sometimes called the strip of absolute convergence.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is analytic in the region of absolute convergence: this is a consequence of Fubini's theorem and Morera's theorem.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Similarly, the set of values for which *F*(*s*) converges (conditionally or absolutely) is known as the region of conditional convergence, or simply the **region of convergence** (ROC).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] If the Laplace transform converges (conditionally) at *s* = *s*0, then it automatically converges for all *s* with Re(*s*) > Re(*s*0).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Therefore, the region of convergence is a half-plane of the form Re(*s*) > *a*, possibly including some points of the boundary line Re(*s*) = *a*.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] That is, *F*(*s*) can effectively be expressed, in the region of convergence, as the absolutely convergent Laplace transform of some other function.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] There are several PaleyŌĆōWiener theorems concerning the relationship between the decay properties of *f*, and the properties of the Laplace transform within the region of convergence.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In engineering applications, a function corresponding to a linear time-invariant (LTI) system is *stable* if every bounded input produces a bounded output.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This is equivalent to the absolute convergence of the Laplace transform of the impulse response function in the region Re(*s*) Ōēź 0.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] As a result, LTI systems are stable, provided that the poles of the Laplace transform of the impulse response function have negative real part.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This ROC is used in knowing about the causality and stability of a system.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform's key property is that it converts differentiation and integration in the time domain into multiplication and division by *s* in the Laplace domain.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Thus, the Laplace variable *s* is also known as an *operator variable* in the Laplace domain: either the *derivative operator* or (for *s*ŌłÆ1) the *integration operator*.
