[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform can be viewed as a continuous analogue of a power series.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] If *a*(*n*) is a discrete function of a positive integer *n*, then the power series associated to *a*(*n*) is the series $\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a(n)x^{n}$ where *x* is a real variable (see *Z-transform*).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Replacing summation over *n* with integration over *t*, a continuous version of the power series becomes $\int _{0}^{\infty }f(t)x^{t}\,dt$ where the discrete function *a*(*n*) is replaced by the continuous one *f*(*t*).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] For this to converge for, say, all bounded functions *f*, it is necessary to require that ln *x* < 0.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In other words, the Laplace transform is a continuous analog of a power series, in which the discrete parameter *n* is replaced by the continuous parameter *t*, and *x* is replaced by *e*ŌłÆ*s*.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Analogously to a power series, if ŌüĀ $a(n)=O(\rho ^{-n})$ ŌüĀ, then the power series converges to an analytic function in ŌüĀ $\vert x\vert <\rho$ ŌüĀ, if ŌüĀ $f(t)=O(e^{-\sigma t})$ ŌüĀ, the Laplace transform converges to an analytic function for ŌüĀ $\Re (s)>\sigma$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] It is often convenient to use the differentiation property of the Laplace transform to find the transform of a function's derivative.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The above formula is a variation of integration by parts, with the operators ${\frac {d}{dx}}$ and $\int \,dx$ being replaced by ${\mathcal {L}}$ and ŌüĀ ${\mathcal {L}}^{-1}$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] By plugging in $({\mathcal {L}}f)(x)=\int _{0}^{\infty }f(s)e^{-sx}\,ds$ the left-hand side turns into: $\int _{0}^{\infty }\int _{0}^{\infty }f(s)g(x)e^{-sx}\,ds\,dx,$ but assuming Fubini's theorem holds, by reversing the order of integration we get the wanted right-hand side.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This method can be used to compute integrals that would otherwise be difficult to compute using elementary methods of real calculus.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The function *g* is assumed to be of bounded variation.
