[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] In general, the LaplaceŌĆōStieltjes transform is the Laplace transform of the Stieltjes measure associated to g.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] So in practice, the only distinction between the two transforms is that the Laplace transform is thought of as operating on the density function of the measure, whereas the LaplaceŌĆōStieltjes transform is thought of as operating on its cumulative distribution function.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Let f be a complex-valued Lebesgue integrable function supported on ŌüĀ $[0,\infty )$ ŌüĀ, and let $F(s)={\mathcal {L}}f(s)$ be its Laplace transform.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Then, within the region of convergence, we have $F(\sigma +i\tau )=\int _{0}^{\infty }f(t)e^{-\sigma t}e^{-i\tau t}\,dt,$ which is the Fourier transform of the function ŌüĀ $f(t)e^{-\sigma t}$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Indeed, the Fourier transform is a special case (under certain conditions) of the bilateral Laplace transform.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The main difference is that the Fourier transform of a function is a complex function of a *real* variable (frequency ŌüĀ $\tau$ ŌüĀ), the Laplace transform of a function is a complex function of a *complex* variable (damping factor $\sigma$ and frequency ŌüĀ $\tau$ ŌüĀ).
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] The Laplace transform is usually restricted to transformation of functions of *t* with *t* Ōēź 0.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] A consequence of this restriction is that the Laplace transform of a function is a holomorphic function of the variable *s*.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Unlike the Fourier transform, the Laplace transform of a distribution is generally a well-behaved function.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] Techniques of complex variables can also be used to directly study Laplace transforms.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] As a holomorphic function, the Laplace transform has a power series representation.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This power series expresses a function as a linear superposition of moments of the function.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p01] This perspective has applications in probability theory.
