[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p02] Then the limit as ŌüĀ x ŌüĀ goes to infinity of ŌüĀ $e^{-x}A(x)$ ŌüĀ is equal to ŌüĀ c ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/laplace-transform-p02] This statement can be applied in particular to the logarithmic derivative of Riemann zeta function, and thus provides an extremely short way to prove the prime number theorem.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] In engineering, a **transfer function** (also known as **system function** or **network function**) of a system, sub-system, or component is a mathematical function that models the system's output for each possible input.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] It is widely used in electronic engineering tools like circuit simulators and control systems and in chemical reaction engineering for the study and modeling of the residence time distribution and stability of a reactor.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] In simple cases, this function can be represented as a two-dimensional graph of an independent scalar input versus the dependent scalar output (known as a **transfer curve** or **characteristic curve**).
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] Transfer functions for components are used to design and analyze systems assembled from components, particularly using the block diagram technique, in electronics and control theory.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] Dimensions and units of the transfer function model the output response of the device for a range of possible inputs.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The term *transfer function* is also used in the frequency domain analysis of systems using transform methods, such as the Laplace transform; it is the amplitude of the output as a function of the frequency of the input signal.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The transfer function of an electronic filter is the amplitude at the output as a function of the frequency of a constant amplitude sine wave applied to the input.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] For optical imaging devices, the optical transfer function is the Fourier transform of the point spread function (a function of spatial frequency).
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] Transfer functions are commonly used in the analysis of systems such as single-input single-output filters in signal processing, communication theory, and control theory.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The term is often used exclusively to refer to linear time-invariant (LTI) systems.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] Most real systems have non-linear inputŌĆōoutput characteristics, but many systems operated within nominal parameters (not over-driven) have behavior close enough to linear that LTI system theory is an acceptable representation of their inputŌĆōoutput behavior.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] Descriptions are given in terms of a complex variable, $s=\sigma +j\cdot \omega$ .
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] In many applications it is sufficient to set $\sigma =0$ (thus $s=j\cdot \omega$ ), which reduces the Laplace transforms with complex arguments to Fourier transforms with the real argument Žē.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] This is common in applications primarily interested in the LTI system's steady-state response (often the case in signal processing and communication theory), not the fleeting turn-on and turn-off transient response or stability issues.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] Discrete-time signals may be notated as arrays indexed by an integer n (e.g. $x[n]$ for input and $y[n]$ for output).
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] where *u* and *r* are suitably smooth functions of *t*, has *L* as the operator defined on the relevant function space that transforms *u* into *r*.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] That kind of equation can be used to constrain the output function *u* in terms of the *forcing* function *r*.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The transfer function can be used to define an operator $F[r]=u$ that serves as a right inverse of *L*, meaning that $L[F[r]]=r$ .
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] Solutions of the homogeneous constant-coefficient differential equation $L[u]=0$ can be found by trying $u=e^{\lambda t}$ .
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The inhomogeneous case can be easily solved if the input function *r* is also of the form $r(t)=e^{st}$ .
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] A general sinusoidal input to a system of frequency $\omega _{0}/(2\pi )$ may be written $\exp(j\omega _{0}t)$ .
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The response of a system to a sinusoidal input beginning at time $t=0$ will consist of the sum of the steady-state response and a transient response.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The steady-state response is the output of the system in the limit of infinite time, and the transient response is the difference between the response and the steady-state response; it corresponds to the homogeneous solution of the differential equation.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] where *sPi* are the *N* roots of the characteristic polynomial and will be the poles of the transfer function.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] In a transfer function with a single pole $H(s)={\frac {1}{s-s_{P}}}$ where $s_{P}=\sigma _{P}+j\omega _{P}$ , the Laplace transform of a general sinusoid of unit amplitude will be ${\frac {1}{s-j\omega _{0}}}$ .
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The second term in the numerator is the transient response, and in the limit of infinite time it will diverge to infinity if *ŽāP* is positive.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] For a system to be stable, its transfer function must have no poles whose real parts are positive.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] If the transfer function is strictly stable, the real parts of all poles will be negative and the transient behavior will tend to zero in the limit of infinite time.
