[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] From the complex identity $z=|z|e^{j\arg(z)}$ , the argument follows.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] In a linear time-invariant system, the input frequency $\omega$ has not changed; only the amplitude and phase angle of the sinusoid have been changed by the system.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The transfer function can also be shown using the Fourier transform, a special case of bilateral Laplace transform where $s=j\omega$ .
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] In control engineering and control theory, the transfer function is derived with the Laplace transform.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] The transfer function was the primary tool used in classical control engineering.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] A transfer matrix can be obtained for any linear system to analyze its dynamics and other properties; each element of a transfer matrix is a transfer function relating a particular input variable to an output variable.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] A representation bridging state space and transfer function methods was proposed by Howard H.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] Rosenbrock, and is known as the Rosenbrock system matrix.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] In imaging, transfer functions are used to describe the relationship between the scene light, the image signal and the displayed light.
[src:laplace-transform/transfer-function] Transfer functions do not exist for many non-linear systems, such as relaxation oscillators; however, describing functions can sometimes be used to approximate such nonlinear time-invariant systems.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] In mathematics, the **two-sided Laplace transform** or **bilateral Laplace transform** is an integral transform equivalent to probability's moment-generating function.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Two-sided Laplace transforms are closely related to the Fourier transform, the Mellin transform, the Z-transform and the ordinary or one-sided Laplace transform.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] There seems to be no generally accepted notation for the two-sided transform; the ${\mathcal {B}}$ used here recalls "bilateral".
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] In pure mathematics the argument ŌüĀ t ŌüĀ can be any variable, and Laplace transforms are used to study how differential operators transform the function.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] In science and engineering applications, the argument ŌüĀ t ŌüĀ often represents time (in seconds), and the function ŌüĀ $f(t)$ ŌüĀ often represents a signal or waveform that varies with time.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] In these cases, the signals are transformed by filters, that work like a mathematical operator, but with a restriction.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] They have to be causal, which means that the output at a given time ŌüĀ t ŌüĀ cannot depend on an input that occurs at later time ŌüĀ $t'$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] In population ecology, the argument ŌüĀ t ŌüĀ often represents spatial displacement in a dispersal kernel.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] When working with functions of time, ŌüĀ $f(t)$ ŌüĀ is called the **time domain** representation of the signal, while ŌüĀ $F(s)$ ŌüĀ is called the **s-domain** (or *Laplace domain*) representation.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] The inverse transformation then represents a *synthesis* of the signal as the sum of its frequency components taken over all frequencies, whereas the forward transformation represents the *analysis* of the signal into its frequency components.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Laplace transform is often used in control theory and signal processing, as it generally deals with linear causal system responses that may grow exponentially.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] The Fourier transform integral fails to converge for exponentially growing signals, which means that a linear, shift-invariant system described by it is stable or critical.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] The Laplace transform, on the other hand, will somewhere converge for every (causal) impulse response that grows at most exponentially.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Since there are no superexponentially growing linear feedback networks, Laplace transform based analysis and solution of linear, shift-invariant systems, takes its most general form in the context of Laplace, rather than Fourier, transforms.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Laplace transform theory falls within the ambit of more general integral transforms, or even general harmonic analysis.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] In that framework and nomenclature, Laplace transforms are simply a form of Fourier analysis, though more general.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] where ŌüĀ $m:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} :x\mapsto -x$ ŌüĀ is the function that multiplies by minus one, so either version of the Laplace transform can be defined in terms of the other.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] The moment-generating function of a continuous probability density function ŌüĀ $f(x)$ ŌüĀ can be expressed as ŌüĀ ${\mathcal {B}}\{f\}(-s)$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] This theorem is proved by applying the inverse Laplace transform on the convolution theorem in form of the cross-correlation.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Let ŌüĀ $f(t)$ ŌüĀ be a function with bilateral Laplace transform ŌüĀ $F(s)$ ŌüĀ in the strip of convergence ŌüĀ $\alpha <\Re (s)<\beta$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Bilateral transform requirements for convergence are more difficult than for unilateral transforms.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] The region of convergence will be normally smaller.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] The Laplace transform is usually understood as conditionally convergent, meaning that it converges in the former instead of the latter sense.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] The set of values for which ŌüĀ $F(s)$ ŌüĀ converges absolutely is either of the form ŌüĀ $\Re (s)>a$ ŌüĀ or else ŌüĀ $\Re (s)\geq a$ ŌüĀ, where ŌüĀ a ŌüĀ is an extended real constant, ŌüĀ $-\infty \leq a\leq \infty$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] (This follows from the dominated convergence theorem.) The constant ŌüĀ a ŌüĀ is known as the abscissa of absolute convergence, and depends on the growth behavior of ŌüĀ $f(t)$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Analogously, the two-sided transform converges absolutely in a strip of the form ŌüĀ $a<\Re (s)<b$ ŌüĀ, and possibly including the lines ŌüĀ $\Re (s)=a$ ŌüĀ or ŌüĀ $\Re (s)=b$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] The subset of values of ŌüĀ s ŌüĀ for which the Laplace transform converges absolutely is called the region of absolute convergence or the domain of absolute convergence.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] The Laplace transform is analytic in the region of absolute convergence.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Similarly, the set of values for which ŌüĀ $F(s)$ ŌüĀ converges (conditionally or absolutely) is known as the region of conditional convergence, or simply the **region of convergence** (ROC).
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] If the Laplace transform converges (conditionally) at ŌüĀ $s=s_{0}$ ŌüĀ, then it automatically converges for all ŌüĀ s ŌüĀ with ŌüĀ $\Re (s)>\Re (s_{0})$ ŌüĀ).
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Therefore, the region of convergence is a half-plane of the form ŌüĀ $\Re (s)>a$ ŌüĀ, possibly including some points of the boundary line ŌüĀ $\Re (s)=a$ ŌüĀ.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] That is, in the region of convergence ŌüĀ $F(s)$ ŌüĀ can effectively be expressed as the absolutely convergent Laplace transform of some other function.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] There are several PaleyŌĆōWiener theorems concerning the relationship between the decay properties of ŌüĀ f ŌüĀ and the properties of the Laplace transform within the region of convergence.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] Bilateral transforms do not respect causality.
[src:laplace-transform/two-sided-laplace-transform] They make sense when applied over generic functions but when working with functions of time (signals) unilateral transforms are preferred.
